{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17650563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17650563"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:13:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:13:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18411"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18411"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11129"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74513"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11129"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18411"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60004"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"10787"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25796"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25799"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74513"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a novel approach being developed for the treatment of facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy (FSHD)?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gene therapy to silence DUX4 expression","Stem cell transplantation to regenerate muscle tissue","Use of corticosteroids to reduce muscle inflammation","Physical therapy to improve muscle strength","Nutritional supplements to enhance muscle function"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGene therapy to silence DUX4 expression\u003C/strong\u003E is a novel approach being developed for the treatment of FSHD. FSHD is caused by the inappropriate expression of the DUX4 gene, which leads to muscle degeneration. By targeting and silencing DUX4, gene therapy aims to address the root cause of the disease and prevent further muscle damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStem cell transplantation\u003C/strong\u003E is a potential treatment for various muscular dystrophies, but it is not currently a primary focus for FSHD treatment. The challenge lies in ensuring the transplanted cells can integrate and function effectively in the affected muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUse of corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E is a common treatment for other types of muscular dystrophy, such as Duchenne muscular dystrophy, to reduce inflammation and slow disease progression. However, they are not a novel approach for FSHD and do not target the underlying genetic cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhysical therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is an important supportive treatment to maintain muscle function and mobility in FSHD patients, but it does not address the genetic basis of the disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENutritional supplements\u003C/strong\u003E may support overall health and muscle function, but they are not a targeted treatment for the genetic cause of FSHD.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy (FSHD) is a genetic muscle disorder caused by the inappropriate expression of the DUX4 gene.","Current research is focused on developing treatments that target the underlying genetic and molecular mechanisms of FSHD.","Modulating the expression of DUX4 is a promising therapeutic strategy for FSHD."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s 